Return only a corrected Java rule method body if the failure is likely a rule logic error.
Do not include package, imports, class declarations, annotations, method declarations,
markdown, or explanations.
Use only ModuleAlgBase APIs that compile and match the SDK profile.

When SDK profile is POST, use only POST instance-view APIs such as parameter(code).setValue(...),
part(code).setQuantity(...), partCategory(code).parameter(code).setValue(...),
partCategory(code).part(code).setQuantity(...), partCategory(code).sumQuantity(),
and partCategorySum(code).sumDynAttr4Int(...). Wrap numeric parameter writeback values with
String.valueOf(...). Do not use model(), onlyEnforceIf(...), inCompatible(...), or priority APIs.
For POST category quantity totals, use partCategory("categoryCode").sumQuantity().
Use partCategorySum("categoryCode") only for dynamic-attribute aggregation such as
sumDynAttr4Int(...), dynAttr(...), or dynAttrs(...). Never call
partCategorySum("categoryCode").sumQuantity() or partCategorySum("categoryCode").quantity().

When SDK profile is CONSTRAINT, use constraint-model APIs such as model().sum4Selected(...),
model().sum4Quantity(...), model().addLessOrEqual(...), model().addGreaterOrEqual(...),
model().addEquality(...), and inCompatible(ruleCode, "category:Attr=value", "category:Attr=value").
model().addBoolAnd and model().addBoolOr accept exactly one AlgCPLiteral[] argument. To bind a
BoolVar to a conjunction or disjunction, use onlyEnforceIf on both the true and false directions;
do not call model().addBoolAnd(cond, a, b) or model().addBoolOr(cond, a, b).
model().addEquality(...), model().addDifferent(...), model().addLessOrEqual(...),
model().addGreaterOrEqual(...), and similar numeric APIs return AlgCPConstraint, not AlgCPLiteral.
Never put those calls inside AlgCPLiteral[] and never pass them to model().addImplication(...).
To use a numeric predicate as a boolean literal, first create an AlgCPBoolVar and bind both directions
with addEquality(...).onlyEnforceIf(eqVar) and addDifferent(...).onlyEnforceIf(eqVar.not()).
model().addImplication(left, right) accepts AlgCPLiteral arguments only, such as BoolVar, hiddenVar(),
option(...).selectedVar(), or their .not() forms.
Linear expression terms use addTerm(variable, coefficient), such as
expr.addTerm(para("p1").valueVar(), 1). Do not reverse the arguments.
To combine aggregate PartAlgCPLinearExpr values such as model().sum4Quantity(...) or
model().sum4Selected(...), use compositeExpr.addExpr(aggregateExpr, coefficient). Do not pass
aggregate expressions to addTerm(...).
PartAlgCPLinearExpr is also a linear expression. It can be used in numeric constraints such as
model().addGreaterOrEqual(totalExpr, para("p1").valueVar()). When comparing an aggregate expression
with a parameter, use para("p1").valueVar(), not the ParaVar itself.
For hidden helper calls, use addVarAboutHiddenConstraints(para("p1"), para("p2")) or
addVarAboutHiddenConstraints(partVar("part1"), partVar("part2")). Do not pass ruleCode, hiddenVar(),
valueVar(), or BoolVar, and do not call it through model().
If a rule can hide a parameter or part, call addVarAboutHiddenConstraints(...) for every parameter
or part whose hiddenVar() is controlled by the rule. Without this registration, the engine adds default
visible constraints and hidden solutions can become impossible.
For aggregate quantity or weighted dynamic-attribute totals, prefer
model().sum4Quantity("categoryCodeOrCommaSeparatedCodes", "attrCodeOrBlank", "optional Attr=value filter");
the attrCode argument is a numeric weighting attribute, not a filter attribute. For selected-count rules,
use attrCode "" and put attribute predicates in the filter condition. For total part quantity rules,
also use attrCode "" unless the rule says weighted by a numeric dynamic attribute.
cross-category module-level totals use comma-separated category codes, module-level all-instance
multi-instance totals use categoryCode*, and part-category effectScope=AllInst rules should use the
two-argument overloads model().sum4Quantity("attrCode", "filter") or model().sum4Selected("attrCode", "filter").
Do not add * only because a category supports multi-instance; use * only when the natural language explicitly
asks for all instances of that category. Do not mix * and comma-separated categories in one aggregate call,
such as "disk*,mainBoard"; if a true rule needs that shape, build separate aggregate expressions and combine
them with model().newPartLinearExpr(...).addExpr(...).
Aggregate totals should not be built by enumerating atomic parts with partVar(...).quantityVar().
In filter conditions, use dynamic attribute values from context dynAttr or option codeValue, not option codes.
Filter conditions are rule-engine strings such as Attr=value or Attr>=number; do not use Java == and do
not quote string values inside the filter.
For priority rules, add the normal hard constraints first. Then build a separate objective expression
with PartAlgCPLinearExpr from model().newPartLinearExpr("name"), combine aggregate expressions with
addExpr(...), call model().setObjectExpr(expr), and call updatePriorityObjectFuntion(ruleCode, expr).
model().newPartLinearExpr requires a name string.
Do not use POST instance-view APIs such as parameter(...).setValue(...), partCategorySum(...),
part(...), or partCategory(...).
